To the cook in Chandler, Arizona: chill out!I'm sure you'll never visit this recipe again or the reviews, but if you do, I have just a couple of things to say to you: 1) I can tell you are a young, budding cook. You are experimenting with things, and that is VERY good; 2) You are young, I think, and haven't ever pawed through recipe books and indexes etc. If you have, GREAT, but, you seem disturbed by the number of people who DID like this recipe, and you were allowed the internet forum to express your anger toward this recipe; 3) Everyone has a different taste for things, and up until epicurious came along, there really wasn't the forum to discuss how good or bad a recipe was. I am sorry you found this particular recipe to "suck", but I think what irks you is that so many people did like it and you couldn't understand why. I hope you can pull it together. Cooking can be stressful, but for me it is therapeutic....keep your mind open.... It isn't the best, but it isn't bad, and up until the internet came along, many of us were pretty alone in our cooking. I love the Epicurious forum because it is a chance for feedback. Prior to that, I threw a lot of expensive food in the trash because it just didn't taste good enough, and of course, that is weighing in cost and labor intensity. Of course what you like is important, but if you want to cook well, you must be willing to take risks, and experience those failures. Sorry that this one was a failure for you, and maybe with some maturity in cooking you will use the epicurious website better--and the internet overall--better as well.

