Rating: 3
This makes a fabulous and impressive dinner for guests. I've made this twice now, and everyone just loves it. The second time was even better. The best part is that it can be made the day before. True, the stuffing of the thighs are a bit time consuming. I spent a total of 2 hours in the kitchen from start to finish (that includes clean-up). If you're going to buy thighs that are already skinned and deboned, try to find the largest ones---that will make it easier. I was able to stuff 13 small thighs with this recipe. Only made the following adjustments to the recipe: used 2 14-oz cans of low sodium broth and a 28-oz can of the puree tomatoes. Only spent $7 on my Chianti, so I didn't think that was too pricey as others have complained about the cost of Chianti. The sauce is delicious. Other reviewers had problems thickening the sauce---the key is to have your heat on high to reduce and thicken it. I served this over campanelle and fresh chopped spinach. You know this recipe is a hit when your dinner guests ask if there are any left-overs to take home. This is a definite keeper!

